WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:03.280
Since the beginning of time on&nbsp;
our planet, tectonic plates have

00:00:03.280 --> 00:00:08.720
been slow dancing on earth's uppermost mantle.
Where they touch, earth's brittle skin reveals the

00:00:08.720 --> 00:00:15.200
immense forces beneath through towering mountains,&nbsp;
sudden earthquakes, and vast canyons diverging.

00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:21.040
The most accessible example of such a divergent&nbsp;
zone is the Great Rift Valley, which has impacted

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:26.880
the topography from southern Turkey through the&nbsp;
horn of Africa, all the way down to Mozambique.

00:00:26.880 --> 00:00:31.920
The system is especially pronounced in East&nbsp;
Africa, where the parting of the Somali and

00:00:31.920 --> 00:00:37.680
Nubian Plate has formed the Albertine Rift&nbsp;
full of rugged ridges and deep valleys.

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:42.640
The deepest and largest of these valleys have&nbsp;
eventually filled with Africa's abundant tropical

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:48.480
rainfall and are now forming the African Great&nbsp;
lakes. Along the 3000 kilometer long crescent,

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:55.200
a series of 7 major lakes have captured 25% of the&nbsp;
world's freshwater and the southernmost one, Lake

00:00:55.200 --> 00:01:00.880
Malawi is home to some fascinating peculiarities,&nbsp;
which we will explore in this video.

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:04.720
Before we get into the oddities however,&nbsp;
let’s lay some groundwork and quickly go

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:10.560
over the geographical key facts.
Chapter 1: Lake Malawi in numbers

00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:17.440
At 29.600 square kilometers, roughly the&nbsp;
size of Belgium or the US state of Maryland,

00:01:17.440 --> 00:01:22.400
Lake Malawi, or Lake Nyassa as it is called on&nbsp;
the eastern banks in Mozambique and Tanzania,

00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:28.320
ranks among the largest lakes in the world.&nbsp;
The north to south span of over 560 kilometers

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:33.520
follows the shape of the western arm of the East&nbsp;
African Rift Valley, which sank the lakebed over

00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:38.640
2200 meters below the surrounding plateau.&nbsp;
In this valley, Lake Malawi is reaching a&nbsp;

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:44.080
depth of over 700 meters at the deepest section&nbsp;
securing it the rank of the 8th deepest lake of

00:01:44.080 --> 00:01:49.520
the planet with the 4th largest volume of any&nbsp;
freshwater lake. However, this level is just a

00:01:49.520 --> 00:01:56.240
snapshot in the hydrographic history of the lake.
In 2005, a team of researchers extracted a 380

00:01:56.240 --> 00:01:59.280
meter deep continuous sediment&nbsp;
sample from the lake bottom,

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:04.480
which reveals the past 1.3 million years of&nbsp;
uninterrupted hydrological history and gives

00:02:04.480 --> 00:02:11.120
a detailed timeline of volcanic eruptions, the&nbsp;
climate and changes to the lake’s biodiversity.

00:02:11.120 --> 00:02:16.160
Mapping the readings reveals that the lake has&nbsp;
undergone a total of 24 cycles from flood to

00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:21.360
drought in this period with level swings of over&nbsp;
600 meters changing the lake’s characteristic

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:27.520
from its status as a freshwater tank to a shallow,&nbsp;
saline and alkaline water body and back again.

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:32.400
Today, the surface level has found somewhat of an&nbsp;
equilibrium with the inflow of the lakes drainage

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:36.960
basin, which lies as a narrow band around&nbsp;
the lake sufficing to balance the very high

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:42.080
evaporation rate. The remaining water of this&nbsp;
balance is drained through Lake Malawi's only

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:46.880
outflow through the Shire river in the south,&nbsp;
carrying the water along the rift valley until

00:02:46.880 --> 00:02:51.840
it confluences with the majestic Zambezi River.
Heading back to the lake, it’s finally time

00:02:51.840 --> 00:02:55.760
to look at the curiosities contained in&nbsp;
and around these waters, bringing us to

00:02:55.760 --> 00:03:02.000
Chapter 2: Peculiarities of lake Malawi
Being placed in the middle of a massive graben,

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.880
Lake Malawi is surrounded by uplifted rift&nbsp;
shoulders and as such quite secluded from many

00:03:06.880 --> 00:03:13.120
external influences. In the study of evolutionary&nbsp;
biology, such environments often act similar to

00:03:13.120 --> 00:03:18.560
remote islands and adaptive radiation creates an&nbsp;
abundance of variance in species from a common

00:03:18.560 --> 00:03:23.600
ancestor. Where the Galapagos Islands have the&nbsp;
Finch which were famously studied by Charles

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:29.760
Darwin and served as the foundation for the&nbsp;
theory of evolution, Lake Malawi has the Cichlids.

00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:34.880
This family of small colorful fish has rapidly&nbsp;
evolved along the shores of Lake Malawi,

00:03:34.880 --> 00:03:40.320
with hundreds of closely related but distinct&nbsp;
species sharing the lagoons and rocky shores.

00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:44.560
Due to their distinct chromatic features with&nbsp;
shimmering scales they are the most popular

00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:50.320
ornamental aquarium fish today. From the 2000 species&nbsp;
of Cichlids which have been described globally,

00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:56.000
mainly around the tropics of the Americas, Africa,&nbsp;
India and the Middle East, 800 of these are found

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.280
in Lake Malawi alone, making it a true wild&nbsp;
aquarium and the most species rich lake in

00:04:01.280 --> 00:04:06.720
the world. For the local communities, these fish&nbsp;
are the backbone of their nutritional balance,

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:12.160
presenting 40% of the people’s protein intake.&nbsp;
An exploding population around the lake and the

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:16.852
resulting overfishing has put a massive strain&nbsp;
on the fish population in recent decades though,

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:22.240
but a partnership of NGOs and local authorities&nbsp;
are actively pushing a transition from fishing

00:04:22.240 --> 00:04:26.960
to fish-farming, which will alleviate&nbsp;
the strain on the natural habitats.

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:31.840
Cichlids are not the only source of animal protein&nbsp;
around the lake however. There is another species

00:04:31.840 --> 00:04:37.520
which thrives in the unique conditions of the lake&nbsp;
and forms an integral part of the local’s diet.

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:42.480
When environmental conditions align, clouds&nbsp;
the size of skyscrapers are rising from the

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:47.920
center of the lake and perform a dance lasting&nbsp;
just a few days. These clouds are not a weather

00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:53.280
phenomenon though, but instead the adult form&nbsp;
of the Chaoborus Edulis, which transforms from

00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:58.800
its glassworm state into the lake fly in the&nbsp;
hundreds of billions. Whenever the population

00:04:58.800 --> 00:05:03.920
erupts and the black clouds rise in the distance,&nbsp;
the lake residents pull out their nets and

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:09.040
harvest the midges to press them into burger&nbsp;
patties or protein bars known as kunga cakes.

00:05:09.040 --> 00:05:14.480
While providing a delicacy to the people living&nbsp;
on the lake shore, the larvae state also plays an

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:19.200
important role for the nutrient cycle within&nbsp;
the lake, extending the habitable zone to

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:23.760
layers way deeper than would otherwise be&nbsp;
possible. As a result of steady temperatures

00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:29.280
and very little in- and outflow of the lake,&nbsp;
Lake Malawi is classified as a meromictic lake,

00:05:29.280 --> 00:05:34.320
which means that its waterlayers experience little&nbsp;
to no mixing. As a consequence of this,

00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:39.360
organic matter and nutrients are often trapped&nbsp;
in the bright upper layers of the lake,

00:05:39.360 --> 00:05:43.920
but this is where the glassworm comes in.
To evade predators in daylight, hundreds of

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:49.040
billions of glassworms migrate from the light&nbsp;
to the dark columns at dawn, down to depths of

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:54.560
around 200 meters. Their daily migration creates&nbsp;
a natural pump of nutrients to the otherwise

00:05:54.560 --> 00:05:58.649
deep and dark layers, which then allows
larger&nbsp;fauna that feed on these larvae

00:05:58.649 --> 00:06:01.680
to extend way deeper into the lake strata.

00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:05.840
While life in the lake runs like a well&nbsp;
greased machine in predictable cycles,

00:06:05.840 --> 00:06:09.520
the same can not be said for the political&nbsp;
situation of the Nations surrounding the

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:14.480
shore. For decades now, the situation around&nbsp;
Lake Malawi has been tense, bringing us to

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:20.800
Chapter 3: The political Geography around Lake Malawi
Zooming on the northern half of the lake

00:06:20.800 --> 00:06:25.040
on Google Maps, two dashed lines are&nbsp;
separating the countries of Malawi and

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:29.537
Tanzania. You can recognize this form of&nbsp;
demarcation from places like the the Kashmir

00:06:29.537 --> 00:06:33.440
region, or Kosovo and it means that there
are some long lasting border

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:38.960
disagreements here. In the case of Lake Malawi,&nbsp;
the convoluted colonial past of the British,

00:06:38.960 --> 00:06:44.400
Portuguese and German occupiers in the region is&nbsp;
leaving the borders of the lake in a stalemate.

00:06:44.400 --> 00:06:49.760
While the Portuguese in Mozambique left with a&nbsp;
1954 agreement in place which splits the lake

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:54.320
in half to the satisfaction of both countries,&nbsp;
the northern section between the British and

00:06:54.320 --> 00:07:01.040
German colonial remnants is more contentious. In&nbsp;
1890, the Heligoland Treaty allocated the entirety

00:07:01.040 --> 00:07:06.720
of this lake section to Nyasaland, the predecessor&nbsp;
of today’s Malawi. With the release of the

00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:13.280
colonial possessions in 1961 and 1964 however,&nbsp;
disagreements quickly arose between the two new

00:07:13.280 --> 00:07:18.800
nations, where Malawi is referring to this treaty,&nbsp;
whereas Tanzania prefers a more modern approach

00:07:18.800 --> 00:07:23.760
to the demarcation of country borders.
Since the 20th century, the territorial

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:27.760
demarcation between neighboring states&nbsp;
across bodies of water has been done through

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:33.280
the principle of equidistance. This principle&nbsp;
was mostly created for delimiting territorial

00:07:33.280 --> 00:07:38.960
waters across seas and channels, but was quickly&nbsp;
adapted to rivers and lakes as well. This has

00:07:38.960 --> 00:07:43.520
since been the foundation of Tanzania's counter&nbsp;
claim instead of following a century old treaty

00:07:43.520 --> 00:07:48.160
that has been drafted by their oppressors.
With the formulation of the law of the sea by the

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:54.400
United Nations in 1982 Tanzania's position only&nbsp;
got stronger, yet Malawi continues to fish and

00:07:54.400 --> 00:08:00.000
license fossil fuel exploration in the disputed&nbsp;
zone. While no armed conflict arose so far,

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.640
talks have been dragging on for decades and&nbsp;
a misinformation campaign by Tanzania with a

00:08:04.640 --> 00:08:09.760
fabricated press release claiming that Malawi has&nbsp;
accepted the convention of the law of the sea has

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:14.880
further fueled the situation in June 2025.&nbsp;
So far there is no end to the disagreement

00:08:14.880 --> 00:08:19.760
in sight and looking back at the immense&nbsp;
population relying on stability in the region

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:25.520
and the resources of the lake, we can just hope a&nbsp;
sustainable and fair solution will be found soon.

00:08:25.520 --> 00:08:30.960
Overall, Lake Malawi is a phenomenon of true&nbsp;
extremes. Built within one of mother nature's

00:08:30.960 --> 00:08:36.560
most ambitious projects currently reshaping the&nbsp;
planet, it fosters an incredible biodiversity

00:08:36.560 --> 00:08:41.360
and should be guarded as a natural treasure&nbsp;
trove. If you want to learn more about the

00:08:41.360 --> 00:08:45.360
most fascinating lakes in the world I can&nbsp;
recommend this video about Lake Baikal,

00:08:45.360 --> 00:08:50.320
the deepest lake in the world, nestled in&nbsp;
another rift valley in the depths of Siberia,

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:57.360
or watch what youtube thinks is best for&nbsp;
you here. See you in the next one, cheers.

